Simulation

James M. Flegal

Agenda

  • Simulating from distributions

Simulation

Why simulate?

  • We want to see what a probability model actually does
  • We want to understand how our procedure works on a test case
  • We want to use a partly-random procedure

All of these require drawing random variables from distributions

Simulation

We have seen R has built in distributions: beta, binom, cauchy, chisq, exp, f, gamma, geom, hyper, logis, lnorm, nbinom, norm, pois, t, tukey, unif, weibull, wilcox, signrank

Every distribution that R handles has four functions.

  • p for "probability", the cumulative distribution function (c. d. f.)
  • q for "quantile", the inverse c. d. f.
  • d for "density", the density function (p. f. or p. d. f.)
  • r for "random", a random variable having the specified distribution

Simulation

  • Usually, R gets Uniform(0,1)(0,1) random variates via a pseudorandom generator, e.g. the linear congruential generator
  • Uses a sequence of Uniform(0,1)(0,1) random variates to generate other distributions
  • How?

Example: Binomial

  • Suppose we want to generate a Binomial(1,1/3)(1,1/3) using a U∼Uniform(0,1)U∼Uniform(0,1)
  • Consider the function X∗=I(0<u<1/3)X∗=I(0<u<1/3), then
    P(X∗=1)=P(I(0<u<1/3=1)=P(u∈(0,1/3))=1/3P(X∗=1)=P(I(0<u<1/3=1)=P(u∈(0,1/3))=1/3
    and P(X∗=0)=2/3P(X∗=0)=2/3
  • Hence, X∗∼Binomial(1,1/3)X∗∼Binomial(1,1/3)
  • Two ways to extend this to Binomial(n,1/3)(n,1/3)

Example: Binomial

my.binom.1 <- function(n=1, p=1/3){
  u <- runif(n)
  binom <- sum(u<p)
  return(binom)
}

my.binom.1(1000)
## [1] 354
my.binom.1(1000, .5)
## [1] 525

Example: Binomial

my.binom.2 <- function(n=1, p=1/3){
  u <- runif(1)
  binom <- qbinom(u, size=n, prob=p)
  return(binom)
}

my.binom.2(1000)
## [1] 349
my.binom.2(1000, .5)
## [1] 493

Quantile transform method

Given U∼Uniform(0,1)U∼Uniform(0,1) and CDF FF from a continuous distribution. Then X=F−1(U)X=F−1(U) is a random variable with CDF FF.

Proof:

P(X≤a)=P(F−1(U)≤a)=P(U≤F(a))=F(a)P(X≤a)=P(F−1(U)≤a)=P(U≤F(a))=F(a)

  • F−1F−1 is the quantile function
  • If we can generate uniforms and calculate quantiles, we can generate non-uniforms
  • Also known as the Probability Integral Transform Method

Example: Exponential

Suppose X∼Exp(β)X∼Exp(β). Then we have density

f(x)=β−1e−x/βI(0<x<∞)f(x)=β−1e−x/βI(0<x<∞)
and CDF
F(x)=1−e−x/βF(x)=1−e−x/β
Also
y=1−e−x/β iff −x/β=log(1−y) iff x=−βlog(1−y).y=1−e−x/β iff −x/β=log⁡(1−y) iff x=−βlog⁡(1−y).
Thus, F−1(y)=−βlog(1−y)F−1(y)=−βlog⁡(1−y).

So if U∼Uniform(0,1)U∼Uniform(0,1), then F−1(u)=−βlog(1−u)∼Exp(β)F−1(u)=−βlog⁡(1−u)∼Exp(β).

Example: Exponential

x <- runif(10000)
y <- - 3 * log(1-x)

## [1] 2.98428

  • But we know the probability density function can we use that?

Rejection sampling

  • The accept-reject algorithm is an indirect method of simulation
  • Uses draws from a density fy(y)fy(y) to get draws from fx(x)fx(x)
  • Sampling from the wrong distribution and correcting it

Rejection sampling

Theorem: Let X∼fxX∼fx and Y∼fyY∼fy where the two densities have common support. Define

M=supxfx(x)fy(x).M=supxfx(x)fy(x).
If M<∞M<∞ then we can generate X∼fxX∼fx as follows,

  1. Generate Y∼fyY∼fy and independently draw U∼Uniform(0,1)U∼Uniform(0,1)
  2. If
    u<fx(y)Mfy(y)u<fx(y)Mfy(y)
    set X=YX=Y; otherwise return to 1.

Exercise: Why is M≥1M≥1?

Rejection sampling

Proof:

P(X≤x)=P(Y≤x|STOP)=P(Y≤x∣∣∣u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=P(Y≤x,u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=ABP(X≤x)=P(Y≤x|STOP)=P(Y≤x|u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=P(Y≤x,u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=AB

Rejection sampling

Now, we have

A=P(Y≤x,u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=E[P(Y≤x,u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))∣∣∣y]=E[I(y≤x)fx(y)Mfy(y)]=∫∞−∞I(y≤x)fx(y)Mfy(y)fy(y)dy=1M∫x−∞fx(y)dy=Fx(x)MA=P(Y≤x,u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=E[P(Y≤x,u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))|y]=E[I(y≤x)fx(y)Mfy(y)]=∫−∞∞I(y≤x)fx(y)Mfy(y)fy(y)dy=1M∫−∞xfx(y)dy=Fx(x)M

Rejection sampling

Similarly, we have

B=P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=E[P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))∣∣∣y]=E[fx(y)Mfy(y)]=∫∞−∞fx(y)Mfy(y)fy(y)dy=1M∫∞−∞fx(y)dy=1MB=P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=E[P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))|y]=E[fx(y)Mfy(y)]=∫−∞∞fx(y)Mfy(y)fy(y)dy=1M∫−∞∞fx(y)dy=1M

Rejection sampling

Hence,

P(X≤x)=AB=Fx(x)M1M=Fx(x)P(X≤x)=AB=Fx(x)M1M=Fx(x)
And the proof is complete. That is, X∼fxX∼fx.

Rejection sampling

  • Notice,
    P(STOP)=B=P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=1MP(STOP)=B=P(u≤fx(y)Mfy(y))=1M
  • Thus the number of iterations until the algorithm stops is Geometric(1/M1/M)
  • Hence, the expected number of iterations until acceptance is MM.

Simulating from mixtures

  • Write f(z)=pf1(z)+(1−p)f2(z)f(z)=pf1(z)+(1−p)f2(z) as the marginal of the joint given by
    f(z|w)=f1(z)I(w=1)+f2(z)I(w=0)f(z|w)=f1(z)I(w=1)+f2(z)I(w=0)
    where W∼Binomial(1,p)W∼Binomial(1,p)
  • Thus to simulate from f(z)f(z)
  1. Draw U∼Uniform(0,1)U∼Uniform(0,1)
  2. If u<pu<p take Z∼f1(z)Z∼f1(z); otherwise take Z∼f2(z)Z∼f2(z)
  • Exercise: Show Z∼f(z)Z∼f(z)

Example: Gamma

ar.gamma <- function(n=100){
x <- double(n)
i <- 1
while(i < (n+1)) {
    u <- runif(1)
    if(u < .5){
        y <- -1 * log(1-runif(1))
    } else {
        y <- sum(-1 * log(1-runif(2)))
    }
    u <- runif(1)
    temp <- 2 * sqrt(y) / (1+y)
    if(u < temp){
        x[i] <- y
        i <- i+1
    }
}
return(x)
}

Example: Gamma

hist(x)

mean(x)
## [1] 1.482398

Example: Beta

Suppose the pdf ff is zero outside an interval [c,d][c,d], and ≤M≤M on the interval.

Example: Beta

We know how to draw from uniform distributions in any dimension. Do it in two:

x1 <- runif(300, 0, 1); y1 <- runif(300, 0, 2.6); 
selected <- y1 < dbeta(x1, 3, 6)

Example: Beta

mean(selected)
## [1] 0.3833333
accepted.points <- x1[selected]
mean(accepted.points < 0.5)
## [1] 0.8521739
pbeta(0.5, 3, 6)
## [1] 0.8554688

Example: Beta

For this to work efficiently, we have to cover the target distribution with one that sits close to it.

x2 <- runif(100000, 0, 1); y2 <- runif(100000, 0, 10); 
selected <- y2 < dbeta(x2, 3, 6)
mean(selected)
## [1] 0.09907

Example: Beta

Alternatives

  • Squeezed rejection sampling may help if evaluating ff is expensive
  • Adaptive rejection sampling may help generate an envelope

Box-Muller

  • Box-Muller transformation transform generates pairs of independent, standard normally distributed random numbers, given a source of uniformly distributed random numbers
  • Let U∼Uniform(0,1)U∼Uniform(0,1) and V∼Uniform(0,1)V∼Uniform(0,1) and set
    R=−2logU−−−−−−−√ and θ=2πVR=−2log⁡U and θ=2πV
  • Then the following transformation yields two independent normal random variates
    X=Rcos(θ) and Y=Rsin(θ)X=Rcos⁡(θ) and Y=Rsin⁡(θ)

Summary

  • Can transform uniform draws into other distributions when we can compute the distribution function
  • Quantile method when we can invert the CDF
  • The rejection method if all we have is the density
  • Basic R commands encapsulate a lot of this for us
  • Optimized algorithms based on distribution and parameter values
